<paper id="1724890242"><title>ElectroMagnetic Analysis (EMA): Measures and Counter-Measures for Smart Cards</title><year>2001</year><authors><author org="Université catholique de Louvain &gt;  &gt;  &gt;  &gt;" id="2195205560">Jean-Jacques Quisquater</author><author org="Université catholique de Louvain &gt;  &gt;  &gt;  &gt;" id="2708458472">David Samyde</author></authors><n_citation>742</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>1506530330</reference><reference>1510418153</reference><reference>1563937974</reference><reference>1565369953</reference><reference>1583816927</reference><reference>1671031071</reference><reference>1897761346</reference><reference>2170489924</reference><reference>2338843535</reference></references><venue id="106296714" type="J">Lecture Notes in Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-45418-7_17</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.5015">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.44447">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.44523">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.42688">Continuation</keyword><keyword weight="0.5111">Smart card</keyword><keyword weight="0.46599">Electromagnetism</keyword><keyword weight="0.54273">Tamper resistance</keyword><keyword weight="0.41352">Electromagnetic radiation</keyword><keyword weight="0.4581">Electrical engineering</keyword><keyword weight="0.44113">Distributed computing</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Power consumption</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>A processor can leak information by different ways [1], electromagnetic radiations could bc one of them. This idea, was first introduced by Kocher, with timing and power measurements. Here we developed the continuation of his ideas by measuring the field radiated by the processor. Therefore we show that the electromagnetic attack obtains at least the same result as power consumption and consequently must be carefuly taken into account. Finally we enumerate countermeasures to be implemented.</abstract></paper>